thname}`\n  // e.g. incoming request is /products\n  // The new URL is now /en-US/products\n  return NextResponse.redirect(request.nextUrl)\n}\n\nexport const config = {\n  matcher: [\n    // Skip all internal paths (_next)\n    '/((?!_next).*)',\n    // Optional: only run on root (/) URL\n    // '/'\n  ],\n}\n```\n\nFinally, ensure all special files inside `app/` are nested under `app/[lang]`. This enables the Next.js router to dynamically handle different locales in the route, and forward the `lang` parameter to every layout and page. For example:\n\n```tsx filename=\"app/[lang]/page.tsx\" switcher\n// You now have access to the current locale\n// e.g. /en-US/products -> `lang` is \"en-US\"\nexport default async function Page({ params }: PageProps<'/[lang]'>) {\n  const { lang } = await params\n  return ...\n}\n```\n\n```jsx filename=\"app/[lang]/page.js\" switcher\n// You now have access to the current locale\n// e.g. /en-US/products -> `lang` is \"en-US\"\nexport default async function Page({ params }) {\n  const { lang } = await params\n  return ...\n}\n```\n\n> **Good to know:** `PageProps` and `LayoutProps` are globally available TypeScript helpers that provide strong typing for route parameters. See [PageProps](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/page#page-props-helper) and [LayoutProps](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/layout#layout-props-helper) for more details.\n\nThe root layout can also be nested in the new folder (e.g. `app/[lang]/layout.js`).\n\n## Localization\n\nChanging displayed content based on the user’s preferred locale, or localization, is not something specific to Next.js. The patterns described below would work the same with any web application.\n\nLet’s assume we want to support both English and Dutch content inside our application. We might maintain two different “dictionaries”, which are objects that give us a mapping from some key to a localized string. For example:\n\n```json filename=\"dictionaries/en.json\"\n{\n  \"products\": {\n    \"cart\": \"Add to Cart\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n```json filename=\"dictionaries/nl.json\"\n{\n  \"products\": {\n    \"cart\": \"Toevoegen aan Winkelwagen\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWe can then create a `getDictionary` function to load the translations for the requested locale:\n\n```ts filename=\"app/[lang]/dictionaries.ts\" switcher\nimport 'server-only'\n\nconst dictionaries = {\n  en: () => import('./dictionaries/en.json').then((module) => module.default),\n  nl: () => import('./dictionaries/nl.json').then((module) => module.default),\n}\n\nexport type Locale = keyof typeof dictionaries\n\nexport const hasLocale = (locale: string): locale is Locale =>\n  locale in dictionaries\n\nexport const getDictionary = async (locale: Locale) => dictionaries[locale]()\n```\n\n```js filename=\"app/[lang]/dictionaries.js\" switcher\nimport 'server-only'\n\nconst dictionaries = {\n  en: () => import('./dictionaries/en.json').then((module) => module.default),\n  nl: () => import('./dictionaries/nl.json').then((module) => module.default),\n}\n\nexport const hasLocale = (locale) => locale in dictionaries\n\nexport const getDictionary = async (locale) => dictionaries[locale]()\n```\n\nGiven the currently selected language, we can fetch the dictionary inside of a layout or page.\n\nSince `lang` is typed as `string`, using `hasLocale` narrows the type to your supported locales. It also ensures a 404 is returned if a translation is missing, rather than a runtime error.\n\n```tsx filename=\"app/[lang]/page.tsx\" switcher\nimport { notFound } from 'next/navigation'\nimport { getDictionary, hasLocale } from './dictionaries'\n\nexport default async function Page({ params }: PageProps<'/[lang]'>) {\n  const { lang } = await params\n\n  if (!hasLocale(lang)) notFound()\n\n  const dict = await getDictionary(lang)\n  return <button>{dict.products.cart}</button> // Add to Cart\n}\n```\n\n```jsx filename=\"app/[lang]/page.js\" switcher\nimport { notFound } from 'next/navigation'\nimport { getDictionary, hasLocale } from './dictionaries'\n\nexport default async function Page({ params }) {\n  const { lang } = await params\n\n  if (!hasLocale(lang)) notFound()\n\n  const dict = await getDictionary(lang)\n  return <button>{dict.products.cart}</button> // Add to Cart\n}\n```\n\nBecause all layouts and pages in the `app/` directory default to [Server Components](/docs/app/getting-started/server-and-client-components), we do not need to worry about the size of the translation files affecting our client-side JavaScript bundle size. This code will **only run on the server**, and only the resulting HTML will be sent to the browser.\n\n## Static Rendering\n\nTo generate static routes for a given set of locales, we can use `generateStaticParams` with any page or layout. This can be global, for example, in the root layout:\n\n```tsx filename=\"app/[lang]/layout.tsx\" switcher\nexport async function generateStaticParams() {\n  return [{ lang: 'en-US' }, { lang: 'de' }]\n}\n\nexport default async function RootLayout({\n  children,\n  params,\n}: LayoutProps<'/[lang]'>) {\n  return (\n    <html lang={(await params).lang}>\n      <body>{children}</body>\n    </html>\n  )\n}\n```\n\n```jsx filename=\"app/[lang]/layout.js\" switcher\nexport async function generateStaticParams() {\n  return [{ lang: 'en-US' }, { lang: 'de' }]\n}\n\nexport default async function RootLayout({ children, params }) {\n  return (\n    <html lang={(await params).lang}>\n      <body>{children}</body>\n    </html>\n  )\n}\n```\n\n## Resources\n\n* [Minimal i18n routing and translations](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/tree/canary/examples/i18n-routing)\n* [`next-intl`](https://next-intl.dev)\n* [`next-international`](https://github.com/QuiiBz/next-international)\n* [`next-i18n-router`](https://github.com/i18nexus/next-i18n-router)\n* [`paraglide-next`](https://inlang.com/m/osslbuzt/paraglide-next-i18n)\n* [`lingui`](https://lingui.dev)\n* [`tolgee`](https://tolgee.io/apps-integrations/next)\n* [`next-intlayer`](https://intlayer.org/doc/environment/nextjs)\n* [`gt-next`](https://generaltranslation.com/en/docs/next)\n---\n\nFor a semantic overview of all documentation, see [/docs/sitemap.md](/docs/sitemap.md)\n\nFor an index of all available documentation, see [/docs/llms.txt](/docs/llms.txt)","durationMs":298,"url":"https://nextjs.org/docs/app/guides/internationalization"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_eds4vwb2zt7w_1","type":"tool_result","content":"Based on the article, here are the key capabilities and recommendations:\n\n**PWA Capabilities Mentioned**\n- **Install criteria**: Apps that meet install requirements can be added to the device, launch from the app launcher, and run in their own window separate from the browser.\n- **Offline support**: Service workers can precache pages and assets; IndexedDB stores data; background sync defers server communication until connection returns.\n- **Push notifications & permission UX**: Permission-triggering APIs (notifications, geolocation, credentials) should only prompt after providing in-context rationale.\n- **App-like experience**: PWAs should feel like part of the device, supporting app-like interactions and behaviors.\n- **Healthy code practices**: Avoid deprecated APIs, `document.write()`, non-passive scroll listeners, and libraries with known vulnerabilities.\n\n**Not Mentioned in Article**\n- App Shortcuts API\n- Badging API\n- iOS Safari PWA support status\n- 2026-specific capabilities\n\n**3-5 Recommendations for a Daily-Use Contemplative App**\n\n1. **Build a core, resilient foundation**: Start with the simplest HTML for core features (e.g., daily readings, session timer) and progressively enhance with CSS and JavaScript, ensuring the app works in any browser.\n\n2. **Prioritize a custom offline experience**: Use a service worker to precache daily content, meditation audio, and a custom offline page, since users will turn to a contemplative app in varied connectivity contexts (retreats, travel, quiet spaces).\n\n3. **Design contextual permission prompts**: If requesting notification permissions for gentle reminders, never prompt on load. Trigger the prompt only after the user engages with a relevant feature, providing clear rationale tied to their practice.\n\n4. **Ensure full responsiveness and input flexibility**: Users may access sessions from phones, tablets, or desktops, and may switch between touch, keyboard, or stylus. Use semantic elements and the Pointer Events API for a seamless experience.\n\n5. **Maintain fast, sustained performance**: Optimize for Core Web Vitals; a slow app disrupts the calm, reflective state your users are seeking. A 123% bounce-rate increase from 1s to 10s load times is especially costly for habit-forming daily use."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"061a3f19-d22b-419e-8188-4f359ca6b060","uuid":"fe4011dc-3a3d-4e06-baae-4318f5bd0e5c","timestamp":"2026-06-11T00:40:05.052Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":139653,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"Based on the article, here are the key capabilities and recommendations:\n\n**PWA Capabilities Mentioned**\n- **Install criteria**: Apps that meet install requirements can be added to the device, launch from the app launcher, and run in their own window separate from the browser.\n- **Offline support**: Service workers can precache pages and assets; IndexedDB stores data; background sync defers server communication until connection returns.\n- **Push notifications & permission UX**: Permission-triggering APIs (notifications, geolocation, credentials) should only prompt after providing in-context rationale.\n- **App-like experience**: PWAs should feel like part of the device, supporting app-like interactions and behaviors.\n- **Healthy code practices**: Avoid deprecated APIs, `document.write()`, non-passive scroll listeners, and libraries with known vulnerabilities.\n\n**Not Mentioned in Article**\n- App Shortcuts API\n- Badging API\n- iOS Safari PWA support status\n- 2026-specific capabilities\n\n**3-5 Recommendations for a Daily-Use Contemplative App**\n\n1. **Build a core, resilient foundation**: Start with the simplest HTML for core features (e.g., daily readings, session timer) and progressively enhance with CSS and JavaScript, ensuring the app works in any browser.\n\n2. **Prioritize a custom offline experience**: Use a service worker to precache daily content, meditation audio, and a custom offline page, since users will turn to a contemplative app in varied connectivity contexts (retreats, travel, quiet spaces).\n\n3. **Design contextual permission prompts**: If requesting notification permissions for gentle reminders, never prompt on load. Trigger the prompt only after the user engages with a relevant feature, providing clear rationale tied to their practice.\n\n4. **Ensure full responsiveness and input flexibility**: Users may access sessions from phones, tablets, or desktops, and may switch between touch, keyboard, or stylus. Use semantic elements and the Pointer Events API for a seamless experience.\n\n5. **Maintain fast, sustained performance**: Optimize for Core Web Vitals; a slow app disrupts the calm, reflective state your users are seeking. A 123% bounce-rate increase from 1s to 10s load times is especially costly for habit-forming daily use.","durationMs":15698,"url":"https://web.dev/articles/pwa-checklist"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_eds4vwb2zt7w_2","type":"tool_result","content":"# WCAG 2.2 AA Requirements for a Chat-Style AI Interface\n\nBased on the 9 new success criteria in WCAG 2.2, a chat-style AI interface would need to address:\n\n**2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum) — AA**\nFocused messages, input field, and send button must remain at least partially visible — not hidden behind sticky headers, toolbars, or chat widgets.\n\n**2.4.13 Focus Appearance — AAA** (advisory for AA)\nUse a focus indicator with a 3:1 contrast ratio between focused and unfocused states, with sufficient size to be clearly visible.\n\n**2.5.7 Dragging Movements — AA**\nAny drag-based gesture (e.g., reordering chat threads) must have a single-pointer alternative such as up/down buttons or a context menu.\n\n**2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum) — AA**\nInteractive controls (send, attach, microphone, emoji) must be at least 24×24 CSS pixels, unless exceptions like spacing, equivalent controls, or inline constraints apply.\n\n**3.2.6 Consistent Help — A**\nIf help mechanisms (contact, self-help, chatbot) appear on multiple pages, they must occur in the same relative order.\n\n**3.3.7 Redundant Entry — A**\nInformation previously entered in the same process should be auto-populated or selectable — don't require re-typing.\n\n**3.3.8 Accessible Authentication (Minimum) — AA**\nLogin must not rely solely on cognitive function tests (puzzles, memorizing passwords, transcribing OTPs) unless an alternative method or assistance mechanism is provided.\n\n---\n\n# WCAG 2.2 AA Requirements for a Daily Push Notification\n\n**2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum) — AA**\nWhen push notification settings receive keyboard focus, the focused element must not be entirely hidden by author-created content (overlays, banners).\n\n**2.4.13 Focus Appearance — AAA** (advisory)\nFocus indicators on notification controls should have a 3:1 contrast ratio and adequate size.\n\n**2.5.7 Dragging Movements — AA**\nAny drag interaction (e.g., swiping to dismiss) must have a non-drag alternative such as a clear/close button.\n\n**2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum) — AA**\nNotification action buttons (snooze, dismiss, open) must be at least 24×24 CSS pixels, or have sufficient spacing from other targets.\n\n**3.2.6 Consistent Help — A**\nIf help is provided in notification settings, it must appear in the same relative location across pages where it repeats.\n\n**3.3.7 Redundant Entry — A**\nDon't require users to re-enter preferences (notification time, frequency) already set earlier in the same process.\n\n**3.3.8 Accessible Authentication (Minimum) — AA**\nAny login triggered by the notification must avoid cognitive function tests, or provide alternatives/assistive mechanisms (e.g., password manager support, copy-paste)."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"061a3f19-d22b-419e-8188-4f359ca6b060","uuid":"49c463cd-4646-4430-8baa-f11b37d0b3c9","timestamp":"2026-06-11T00:40:08.006Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":59829,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# WCAG 2.2 AA Requirements for a Chat-Style AI Interface\n\nBased on the 9 new success criteria in WCAG 2.2, a chat-style AI interface would need to address:\n\n**2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum) — AA**\nFocused messages, input field, and send button must remain at least partially visible — not hidden behind sticky headers, toolbars, or chat widgets.\n\n**2.4.13 Focus Appearance — AAA** (advisory for AA)\nUse a focus indicator with a 3:1 contrast ratio between focused and unfocused states, with sufficient size to be clearly visible.\n\n**2.5.7 Dragging Movements — AA**\nAny drag-based gesture (e.g., reordering chat threads) must have a single-pointer alternative such as up/down buttons or a context menu.\n\n**2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum) — AA**\nInteractive controls (send, attach, microphone, emoji) must be at least 24×24 CSS pixels, unless exceptions like spacing, equivalent controls, or inline constraints apply.\n\n**3.2.6 Consistent Help — A**\nIf help mechanisms (contact, self-help, chatbot) appear on multiple pages, they must occur in the same relative order.\n\n**3.3.7 Redundant Entry — A**\nInformation previously entered in the same process should be auto-populated or selectable — don't require re-typing.\n\n**3.3.8 Accessible Authentication (Minimum) — AA**\nLogin must not rely solely on cognitive function tests (puzzles, memorizing passwords, transcribing OTPs) unless an alternative method or assistance mechanism is provided.\n\n---\n\n# WCAG 2.2 AA Requirements for a Daily Push Notification\n\n**2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum) — AA**\nWhen push notification settings receive keyboard focus, the focused element must not be entirely hidden by author-created content (overlays, banners).\n\n**2.4.13 Focus Appearance — AAA** (advisory)\nFocus indicators on notification controls should have a 3:1 contrast ratio and adequate size.\n\n**2.5.7 Dragging Movements — AA**\nAny drag interaction (e.g., swiping to dismiss) must have a non-drag alternative such as a clear/close button.\n\n**2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum) — AA**\nNotification action buttons (snooze, dismiss, open) must be at least 24×24 CSS pixels, or have sufficient spacing from other targets.\n\n**3.2.6 Consistent Help — A**\nIf help is provided in notification settings, it must appear in the same relative location across pages where it repeats.\n\n**3.3.7 Redundant Entry — A**\nDon't require users to re-enter preferences (notification time, frequency) already set earlier in the same process.\n\n**3.3.8 Accessible Authentication (Minimum) — AA**\nAny login triggered by the notification must avoid cognitive function tests, or provide alternatives/assistive mechanisms (e.g., password manager support, copy-paste).","durationMs":16393,"url":"https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/new-in-22/"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_eds4vwb2zt7w_4","type":"tool_result","content":"# Progressive Disclosure — Definition & Application\n\n## Definition\nProgressive disclosure defers advanced or rarely used features to a secondary screen, reducing initial complexity.\n\n## When to Use\n- Users want both **power** and **simplicity** (conflicting goals).\n- Systems have many features but only a subset is frequently used.\n- Information-rich sites where most users need a core path.\n- Mobile contexts where secondary content should be deferred.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- When you can't correctly split features into \"frequent\" vs. \"rare\" — the initial display still overwhelms users.\n- When 3+ levels of disclosure are needed (users get lost) — simplify instead.\n- When multiple secondary displays crowd the initial screen with too many progression buttons.\n- When the progression mechanic isn't obvious or lacks clear information scent.\n\n## Usability Criteria (the \"two things to get right\")\n1. **Right split** between initial and secondary features — task analysis, frequency-of-use stats, and observational testing reveal what belongs upfront.\n2. **Obvious progression** — visible buttons/links, clear labels that set expectations about what users will find next.\n\n## Staged Disclosure (a variant)\nUsers step through a **linear sequence**, not a hierarchy. Best when task steps have little interaction. Problematic when steps are interdependent.\n\n## 2026 Best Practices for Daily-Contemplative Content Apps\n\nContemplative apps (meditation, daily wisdom, devotionals, Stoic reflections) thrive on simplicity and reduced cognitive load — a perfect fit for progressive disclosure. Updated considerations:\n\n1. **Default to a single insight** as the initial display; treat everything else as secondary.\n2. **Respect the contemplative state** — avoid modals, pop-ups, or aggressive disclosure triggers that interrupt the reflection moment.\n3. **Honor quiet hours** — defer notifications, sharing prompts, and streak features until users explicitly engage deeper.\n4. **Accessibility-first** — disclosure triggers must be keyboard-navigable and screen-reader friendly; contemplative users often include those with cognitive or visual needs.\n5. **Privacy by default** — keep journaling, mood tracking, and personal annotations behind a clear secondary layer, never on the daily card itself.\n6. **Test for depth, not breadth** — user-test whether users discover the deeper layers without forcing them.\n\n## 3–5 Concrete Examples for a \"One Insight Per Day\" Feature\n\n**1. The Daily Card (Initial Display)**\nShows: the insight, a single attribution line, and a minimal \"Reflect\" or \"More\" affordance. That's it. No comments, no stats, no social proof competing for attention.\n\n**2. Expandable Context Layer (Secondary)**\nTapping \"More\" reveals: historical background, source passage, translation notes, and related insights — only when the user wants depth. Keeps the contemplative moment uncluttered.\n\n**3. Optional Journaling, Hidden by Default**\nA \"Save to Journal\" or \"Add a note\" entry point appears as a secondary control. Most days, users simply read and move on; reflective users opt in. Avoid auto-prompting notes — that breaks the stillness.\n\n**4. Streak & Reminder Settings, Buried in Settings**\nGamification metrics (streaks, total insights read) live behind a profile menu, not on the card. Contemplative apps should resist engagement-maximizing UI that contradicts their purpose.\n\n**5. Community Discussion, Tertiary or Off-App**\nIf a community exists, link out to it rather than embedding comments inline. Discussion threads derail reflection. Some apps skip this layer entirely — a valid simplification choice.\n\n## Watch-Outs Specific to Contemplative Apps\n- **Don't disclose too much too soon** — research suggests people understand systems *better* when you help them prioritize, not when you overwhelm them.\n- **Avoid tertiary layers** — if you need a third level (e.g., a teacher dashboard, certification path, or group features), reconsider whether those belong in the same app.\n- **Test the 1-screen vs. 5-screen extremes** — a 2-screen split is often the sweet spot, as the hotel reservation example in the article demonstrates."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"061a3f19-d22b-419e-8188-4f359ca6b060","uuid":"59ff0c8d-bd9f-445f-8863-4d518eceae21","timestamp":"2026-06-11T00:40:19.252Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":119221,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Progressive Disclosure — Definition & Application\n\n## Definition\nProgressive disclosure defers advanced or rarely used features to a secondary screen, reducing initial complexity.\n\n## When to Use\n- Users want both **power** and **simplicity** (conflicting goals).\n- Systems have many features but only a subset is frequently used.\n- Information-rich sites where most users need a core path.\n- Mobile contexts where secondary content should be deferred.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- When you can't correctly split features into \"frequent\" vs. \"rare\" — the initial display still overwhelms users.\n- When 3+ levels of disclosure are needed (users get lost) — simplify instead.\n- When multiple secondary displays crowd the initial screen with too many progression buttons.\n- When the progression mechanic isn't obvious or lacks clear information scent.\n\n## Usability Criteria (the \"two things to get right\")\n1. **Right split** between initial and secondary features — task analysis, frequency-of-use stats, and observational testing reveal what belongs upfront.\n2. **Obvious progression** — visible buttons/links, clear labels that set expectations about what users will find next.\n\n## Staged Disclosure (a variant)\nUsers step through a **linear sequence**, not a hierarchy. Best when task steps have little interaction. Problematic when steps are interdependent.\n\n## 2026 Best Practices for Daily-Contemplative Content Apps\n\nContemplative apps (meditation, daily wisdom, devotionals, Stoic reflections) thrive on simplicity and reduced cognitive load — a perfect fit for progressive disclosure. Updated considerations:\n\n1. **Default to a single insight** as the initial display; treat everything else as secondary.\n2. **Respect the contemplative state** — avoid modals, pop-ups, or aggressive disclosure triggers that interrupt the reflection moment.\n3. **Honor quiet hours** — defer notifications, sharing prompts, and streak features until users explicitly engage deeper.\n4. **Accessibility-first** — disclosure triggers must be keyboard-navigable and screen-reader friendly; contemplative users often include those with cognitive or visual needs.\n5. **Privacy by default** — keep journaling, mood tracking, and personal annotations behind a clear secondary layer, never on the daily card itself.\n6. **Test for depth, not breadth** — user-test whether users discover the deeper layers without forcing them.\n\n## 3–5 Concrete Examples for a \"One Insight Per Day\" Feature\n\n**1. The Daily Card (Initial Display)**\nShows: the insight, a single attribution line, and a minimal \"Reflect\" or \"More\" affordance. That's it. No comments, no stats, no social proof competing for attention.\n\n**2. Expandable Context Layer (Secondary)**\nTapping \"More\" reveals: historical background, source passage, translation notes, and related insights — only when the user wants depth. Keeps the contemplative moment uncluttered.\n\n**3. Optional Journaling, Hidden by Default**\nA \"Save to Journal\" or \"Add a note\" entry point appears as a secondary control. Most days, users simply read and move on; reflective users opt in. Avoid auto-prompting notes — that breaks the stillness.\n\n**4. Streak & Reminder Settings, Buried in Settings**\nGamification metrics (streaks, total insights read) live behind a profile menu, not on the card. Contemplative apps should resist engagement-maximizing UI that contradicts their purpose.\n\n**5. Community Discussion, Tertiary or Off-App**\nIf a community exists, link out to it rather than embedding comments inline. Discussion threads derail reflection. Some apps skip this layer entirely — a valid simplification choice.\n\n## Watch-Outs Specific to Contemplative Apps\n- **Don't disclose too much too soon** — research suggests people understand systems *better* when you help them prioritize, not when you overwhelm them.\n- **Avoid tertiary layers** — if you need a third level (e.g., a teacher dashboard, certification path, or group features), reconsider whether those belong in the same app.\n- **Test the 1-screen vs. 5-screen extremes** — a 2-screen split is often the sweet spot, as the hotel reservation example in the article demonstrates.","durationMs":24468,"url":"https://www.nngroup.com/articles/progressive-disclosure/"}}
